text: We took a day trip from La Paz to Huayna Potosi. We hiked from the refugios (base camp) up to the Glacier where we strapped on crampons, grabbed our ice axes and learned a bit about Alpine/Ice climbing. A storm came through shortly after so we cut our ice climbing adventure short and headed down. We were at almost 5000 meters above sea level and the altitude definitely took it's toll on all of us.

text: While waiting for a weather window to do some longer climbs we checked out the local boulders. It was my first time trying a real outdoor boulder problem and it took me a while to figure out all the moves. I was eventually able to get it and sent a 5b and 5c+ (V1 and V2) on this boulder. I definitely want to try more outdoor bouldering but next time we need a pad and some beta!
author: Kevin

text: I climbed a mountain today! Our weather window finally opened (only a day late) and we were able to get out on the rocks. In the morning we did five sport routes in sector el camina ranging from 5 to 6a (5.8 to 5.10a). The rocks were really neat - it felt more mountainous even on short pitches. Later in the afternoon I climbed the Eagle Needle for my first multi pitch ascent. Four pitches and over 120 metres of climbing to the top. To cap the day we got our best look at the Fitz Roy yet. Poincenot was fully visible and you could see the outline of the Fitz behind some light cloud. Thanks ​Juan Raselli and Mountaineering Patagonia for a great day.
author: Kevin

text: Today we cycled the Circuito Chico. It was a nice ride through north Patagonia. There is a strong Swiss and German influence here and at times it felt like we could be in the Alps.
author: Kevin

places.name: Bariloche
places.address: San Carlos de Bariloche, Río Negro, Argentina

text: Last day of climbing in Patagonia (on this trip) and my first time leading outdoors. I led two routes, both were pretty easy 5.7 or 5.8 but the first one had a fairly high first bolt. Sam Cluthe snapped a photo of me awkwardly clipping. I still have a lot to learn but I was happy with how being on lead didn't affected my climbing at least on an easy pitch. Later in the day I tied in on a 5.11a to try something hard outdoors. Sam  wanted me to struggle for a change since we usually do routes that are hard for her and just right for me. It definitely kicked my butt and it was nice to push myself and fail. I managed to grab the last piece of gear of the wall before calling it. It's too bad we're leaving since that pitch would be a perfect project for me.
author: Kevin

text: After 3 months of backpacking through South America it's time to change continents and explore Eastern Europe. We had a hectic morning getting to the airport but now we're crossing the pond in style - a Boeing 787 Dreamliner! I've wanted to fly in one of these ever since I learned about them in a 4th year aerospace engineering course. Oh and we got upgraded to first class!! 🥂🛫

text: Thinking back to Italy which is just across the Adriatic Sea from me now. There are so many amazing places we aren't going to on this trip. I've come to terms with this and the thought actually comforts me now. We'll never run out of places to travel.

text: New place, same passion, more climbing! Our passports are filling up quickly with all the jumping between countries - this crag was just inside Slovenia. Today we really experienced the difference in climbing grading systems. Most of the pitches were easier but they all had a crux move over a ledge in the middle. With the Yosemite system this move would probably have made the grade higher but the French sport system is more about the whole route. Thanks Natural Croatia Adventure Travel!
author: Kevin

text: Back in Nature! Plitvice Lakes was beautiful but very busy and it's not even high season yet 😮. We were spoiled in Patagonia and crowds are going to take some adjusting to especially as we approach summer time in Europe

text: Climb a mountain in the Alps ☑️ Today we went up the Fleischbank North Ridge to the Meat Bank. It was quite the outing - we hiked 2 hours to the base of the rock then we roped in. We climbed around 12 pitches of 3/3+ with steep hiking interspersed. The route had over 1000 meters of climbing. Views from the summit 👌The way down was no joke either, 2 hours of down climbing and repelling followed by another 2 hours of steep descending. I'm pretty stoked about our first real mountain climb! Huge props to my amazing girlfriend Sam Cluthe who continues to join me on these crazy adventures. Thanks to Explore-Share for setting us up with Mathias Leo who was our great guide for the day.

text: The Old Man of Storr was absolutely spectacular. We were up early to fit everything in today which meant we were just about the only people up there. My trail foo was on point today when I picked the less travelled left fork which took us all the way to the Storr on a much nicer accent with no one else around. I came across the modified signage in the second picture and had to take the photograph. Words to live by.
author: Kevin

text: We went on a Scottish Sea Cliff climbing adventure on the Isle of Skye. After a nice hike in along the coastline and some warm up climbs we traversed along the base of the cliffs to our main route (Fertility Right, Severe). Our guide Mike led with 2 ropes and then Sam followed. They tossed Sam's rope back down to me and then the two of them hauled our gear up before I climbed the pitch. That was enough for Sam so Mike and I rapped back down for another harder route (Jamie Jampot, Very Severe 4C).
author: Kevin

text: We were lucky enough to see lions every day we went to the park. The first day we saw a momma with three cubs. On day two we spotted a pair of lions heading towards a watering hole. On our last day we saw the mother and her cubs again then later on we saw four lions (including two males) crossing a plain 🦁

text:
Apparently yesterday was #worldrhinoday so I'm a day late with this one 😆

Rhinos were one of the only animals we didn't find on day one so I was super excited when we spotted this one under a tree around lunchtime on our second day. Later on we found another one taking a drink at a watering hole. We saw two more on our last day grazing along the main road when we were just driving through the park 🦏
author: Kevin

text: Giraffes were the hardest to photograph especially in groups. Just when they're about to be positioned nicely for the shot they move and make it awkward 🦒

text: Day 1: We hiked through the forest from the Machame Gate up to Machame Camp at 2835m. These tents will be our home for the next six days as we work our way around the mountain camping ever higher up.
author: Kevin

text: Day 2: Making our way from Machame Camp up to Shira Camp at 3750m. It's all smiles in this photo but it was a hard day and we weren't acclimatising as well as we expected.
author: Kevin

text: Day 3: Trekking through the moorland zone to Baranco Camp. Our high point for the day is 4600m at the Lava Tower Camp before descending back to 3900m. We're both struggling to acclimatise so we started taking Diamox - hopefully not too late. Today was a slog, the summit feels far away. We definitely underestimated Kilimanjaro and the altitude.
author: Kevin

text: Day 4: This morning starts with a fun scramble they call Second Breakfast. We continue to Karanga Camp for lunch and it's the most food I've been able to eat in a few days. I'm finally feeling acclimatised. Sam is doing better and confident she can make it to base camp and wait there while Natalie and I go for the summit.
author: Kevin

text: Day 4: I took this photo of our tent with Kibo looming behind at base camp just after 6:00 pm. I'm going to bed right after this to hopefully get five hours of sleep before starting our summit push at midnight.
author: Kevin

text:
Day 5: At 12:15 AM Goodluck, Peter, Natalie and I started our ascent. We reached the summit at 5:40 AM, first from our camp with only a handful of people already there from other routes. It took us just under five and a half hours - any faster my heart and lungs would have quit, any slower and I would have froze. One of the hardest things I've done. 

We took our pictures at the sign quickly and started heading back down the ridge to Stella Point where the sun was just starting to rise. We passed a few large groups and then we were all alone on the ridge when I took these photos. The last photo is us at Stella Point on our way down after the sun was up.
author: Kevin

text: After saying goodbye to our Ryokan Onsen in the morning we took the Shinkansen from Nagano City to Matsumoto to see the castle. It's incredibly beautiful (I took too many photos of it). The town offers free tours so this lovely older Japanese man brought us around the castle, explained the history and how the castle was restored. It's one of the few castles in Japan that is still original.

text: When I first visited Fushimi Inari Shrine five years ago I started up the torii path near the end of the day expecting a short walk because "how many of these gates could they possibly have built". Turns out a lot which resulted in getting to Osaka quite late. This time round we gave ourselves more than enough time and arrived in the morning. Being unprepared had it's benefits though - it is much busier during the day. Luckily stairs tend to weed people out and the crowds thin out the higher you get.

text:
We had an incredible week climbing in Laos. There is so much climbing here! Great variety and a good spread of difficulty. We spent most of our time just exploring and climbing routes within our range.

I couldn't leave without trying a pitch at the roof. It's an intimidating crag - pure overhang and long but the draws are fixed which is nice. I definitely didn't expect to finish when I started climbing. But one bolt at a time with a few "creative" rests and only the anchor remained between me and my first 6b+ send.

I'd just seen my partner fall in this exact spot so I knew it wasn't over yet. I lost both feet for a moment on the last move but was able to recover and get my left back on where I needed it to push over the ledge. The finish wasn't elegant, I laid on the ledge exhausted for a few minutes before clipping.

We didn't get any photos at the roof and it's hard to capture right anyways. Here is a photo of me on our favorite pitch Dancing Butterflies 5c. It wraps up and to the right, slightly overhung with great holds and the moves flow really nicely.
author: Kevin
